<TR>
<TD VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE="margin-left:1.00em; text-indent:-1.00em"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">H. J. Heinz Company</FONT></P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"></TD></TR>
</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px;padding-bottom:0px; "><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Compensation Peer Group companies were selected by the Committee following an August 2012 review
by Mercer of publicly-held companies offering products/services similar to ours, with annual revenue within a range of approximately one-half to two times our annual revenue and market capitalization within a reasonable range of our market
capitalization. The 2013 Compensation Peer Group was composed of companies with annual revenues ranging from $2.7&nbsp;billion to $14.9 billion (measured as of the most recent fiscal year end) and market capitalization ranging from $2.9 billion to
$24.8 billion (measured in the second quarter of 2012). Hershey&#146;s annual revenues of $6.1 billion and market capitalization of $14.9 billion were at the 57</FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1"><SUP
STYLE="vertical-align:baseline; position:relative; bottom:.8ex">th</SUP></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"> and 84</FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1"><SUP
STYLE="vertical-align:baseline; position:relative; bottom:.8ex">th</SUP></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"> percentiles, respectively. Except for Hillshire Brands, all of the companies in our 2013 Compensation Peer Group were
included in our 2012 Compensation Peer Group. Hillshire Brands was added to the Compensation Peer Group for 2013. Sara&nbsp;Lee Corporation, included in 2012, was removed due to its 2012 split into two companies, the larger of which was Hillshire
Brands. At the time of the split, the projected annual revenue of Hillshire Brands fell within the target range and the company was added at the recommendation of Mercer. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Mercer&#146;s benchmarking of our executive officers&#146; compensation is based primarily on the Compensation Peer Group. Data from the Compensation Peer Group is supplemented by composite data from
consumer products companies ranging in size from $3 billion to $15 billion in approximate annual sales. This information is included in three national surveys conducted by Aon Hewitt, Mercer and Towers Watson. The use of the survey composite
provides us with broader, <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">industry-specific</FONT> information regarding pay levels at consumer products companies not only for our named executive officers but also for other executives reporting to our CEO.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px;padding-bottom:0px; "><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Mercer provided the Committee and Company with a report summarizing compensation levels at the 25</FONT><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1"><SUP STYLE="vertical-align:baseline; position:relative; bottom:.8ex">th</SUP></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">, 50</FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1"><SUP
STYLE="vertical-align:baseline; position:relative; bottom:.8ex">th</SUP></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"> and 75</FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1"><SUP
STYLE="vertical-align:baseline; position:relative; bottom:.8ex">th</SUP></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"> percentiles of the Compensation Peer Group and the survey composite data for positions comparable to those held by
each of our executive officers. The Committee also received an analysis from Mercer comparing the target total cash compensation (base salary plus target annual incentive) and target total direct compensation (base salary plus target annual
incentive plus target grant value of <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">long-term</FONT> incentives) for each of the executive officers against these benchmarks. For retention and competitive considerations, the Company targets each executive
officer&#146;s total cash compensation and total direct compensation levels, which include the officer&#146;s base salary, annual incentive and long-term incentive, at the 50</FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1"><SUP
STYLE="vertical-align:baseline; position:relative; bottom:.8ex">th</SUP></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"> percentile of the Compensation Peer Group data or survey composite data applicable to his or her position. The
Committee&#146;s final determinations with respect to base salary, target annual incentive compensation and target <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">long-term</FONT> incentive compensation reflect consideration of the Company&#146;s and the executive
officer&#146;s performance, internal comparisons and other factors the Committee deems appropriate. As a result of these factors, the target total cash compensation and target total direct compensation of our named executive officers in 2013 was
generally set around or below the medians. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">49 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>What other information does the Committee consider when making executive compensation decisions?
</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In addition to the benchmark and other competitive landscape data, the Committee also receives and considers &#147;tally sheet&#148;
information (as described below) relating to the CEO and each of his direct reports. Much of this information is reflected on pages&nbsp;64 through 87 of this proxy statement. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">During 2013, the Committee received detailed tally sheets prepared by management and reviewed by Mercer. Each tally sheet captures comprehensive compensation, benefits and stock ownership data. The tally
sheets provide the Committee with a complete picture of each executive&#146;s current and projected compensation and the amount of each element of compensation or other benefit the executive would receive in the event of voluntary or involuntary
termination, retirement, disability or death. The Committee considers this information, as well as the benchmark information, when making compensation decisions. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Do costs and tax rules play a role? </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">An important factor in the Committee&#146;s
deliberations is the anticipated cost of the various components of executive compensation. Accounting treatment also is taken into consideration in the design and implementation of the annual and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">long-term</FONT>
incentive programs. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Section&nbsp;162(m) of the Internal Revenue Code, or IRC, limits the Company&#146;s ability to deduct certain
compensation in excess of $1&nbsp;million paid to our CEO or to our other named executive officers who are employed on the last day of the fiscal year (other than officers who served as CFO during the year). This limitation does not apply to
compensation that qualifies as <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">&#147;performance-based&#148;</FONT> under applicable Internal Revenue Service regulations or that is paid after termination of employment. The Committee has considered the effect of
Section&nbsp;162(m) of the IRC on the Company&#146;s executive compensation program. It is the Committee&#146;s opinion that, in administering the incentive compensation components of the Company&#146;s executive compensation program, it will
attempt to satisfy the requirements for deductibility under Section&nbsp;162(m) of the IRC. However, the Committee is authorized to exercise discretion in structuring incentive compensation awards and in determining payments in relation to levels of
achievement of performance goals and believes that the total compensation program for executive officers should be managed in accordance with the objectives outlined in the Company&#146;s compensation philosophy and in the best overall interests of
the Company&#146;s stockholders. Accordingly, compensation paid by the Company may not be deductible because such compensation exceeds the limitations, or does not meet the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">&#147;performance-based&#148;</FONT> or
other requirements, for deductibility under Section&nbsp;162(m) of the IRC. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Section&nbsp;409A of the IRC specifies certain rules and
limitations regarding the operation of our deferred compensation plan and other retirement programs. Failure to comply with these rules could subject participants in those plans and programs to additional income tax and interest penalties. We
believe our plans and programs comply with Section&nbsp;409A of the IRC. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">50 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The following charts illustrate the target total direct compensation of our CEO and our named executive officers.

<IMG SRC="g634600g03h00.jpg" ALT="LOGO">
 </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>How are base salaries determined? </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The initial base salary for a new executive officer reflects his or her responsibilities and experience, salaries paid by other companies for comparable executive talent and consideration of
</FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">51 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">
the base salary necessary to recruit the individual to Hershey. A similar approach is applied when adjusting an executive&#146;s base salary to reflect a promotion or significant change in job
responsibilities. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px;padding-bottom:0px; "><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Salary reviews for incumbent officers are generally conducted annually at the beginning of the year.
Each executive officer&#146;s base salary is compared to the range of the 25</FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1"><SUP STYLE="vertical-align:baseline; position:relative; bottom:.8ex">th</SUP></FONT><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"> to 75</FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1"><SUP STYLE="vertical-align:baseline; position:relative; bottom:.8ex">th
</SUP></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">percentiles of the base salary level for the comparable position at the companies in our Compensation Peer Group and the survey composite. Base salaries are targeted at the median, or
50</FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1"><SUP STYLE="vertical-align:baseline; position:relative; bottom:.8ex">th</SUP></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"> percentile. Base salary adjustments, if any, are made
after considering peer group comparisons, Company performance against financial goals, and individual performance. CEO performance is evaluated by the Committee and independent members of the Board. The CEO evaluates performance of his direct
reports, and reviews his recommendations for salary adjustments with the Committee prior to their approval of the base salary level for each executive officer. If an executive officer has responsibility for a particular business unit, the business
unit&#146;s financial results also will be strongly considered. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">On the basis of the foregoing considerations, the Committee, and all
independent directors in the case of our CEO, approved base salaries for 2013 as follows: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">See Column&nbsp;(c) of the Summary Compensation Table on page&nbsp;64 for information regarding the base salary earned by each
of our named executive officers during 2013. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>How is the Company&#146;s annual incentive program designed? How are target annual incentive
amounts and required performance goals established? </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Our executive officers, as well as all other salaried employees globally, are
eligible to receive an annual cash incentive award under the OHIP of our <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">stockholder-approved</FONT> Equity and Incentive Compensation Plan, which we refer to as the Incentive Plan. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The OHIP links the executive officer&#146;s payout opportunity to measures he or she can affect most directly. For 2013, our CEO and all executive
officers reporting directly to him (including the named executive officers) had common financial objectives tied to total Company performance consistent with their responsibility to manage the entire Company. Total Company performance targets are
established in the context of our announced expectations for financial performance, prior year results and market conditions. Nominal or no incentive compensation is paid for missing targets while an appropriate and competitive degree of upside is
included to motivate and reward <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">above-target</FONT> performance. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">52 </FONT></P>

percentage of base salary, contingent upon attainment of Company and individual performance objectives. If target levels are achieved, each of the named executive officers would be eligible to receive an annual incentive award based on the following
target percentages: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px;padding-bottom:0px; "><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In determining the target percentage for each of the executive officers, the Committee compared the
level of target total cash compensation (base salary and target OHIP award) to the benchmark range of the median percentile level for his or her counterparts in the Compensation Peer Group, the survey composite or a blend of the two. For each of the
named executive officers, in 2013 the target total cash compensation generally fell between the 20</FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1"><SUP STYLE="vertical-align:baseline; position:relative; bottom:.8ex">th</SUP></FONT><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"> and 55</FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1"><SUP STYLE="vertical-align:baseline; position:relative; bottom:.8ex">th</SUP></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">
percentiles of target total cash compensation for comparable positions. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The final award earned under the OHIP by participating executive
officers is determined by multiplying the executive officer&#146;s base salary, the applicable target percentage, and performance scores ranging from 0% to 200% based on Company performance and performance against individual performance goals. The
Company performance goals are established at the beginning of each year by the Committee. Individual performance goals also are established at that time. If performance scores exceed the objectives, an individual executive officer may receive more
than his or her target percentage. If scores are below target, the executive officer&#146;s OHIP payout will be below his or her target percentage, subject to no award if performance is below threshold levels. For executive officers in 2013, the
weighting of Company financial performance metrics accounted for 65% of their target award under the program. The remaining 35% of the target award was based upon individual performance toward achievement of up to five individual performance goals
focused on strategic priorities applicable to the named executive officer&#146;s position. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The 65%/35% weighting of Company financial
performance and individual performance reflected a continuation of the 65%/35% weighting used in 2012, a change from the 75%/25% split used prior to 2012. The Committee continued the higher individual performance goal weighting to reinforce the
increased focus on execution of the Company&#146;s top strategic priorities. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>What were the performance targets under the 2013 OHIP? Were
they achieved? What were the final OHIP payouts for 2013? </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The financial performance metrics for our executive officers&#146; OHIP awards
reflected our results-oriented, <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pay-for-performance</FONT></FONT> compensation philosophy. The Company performance objectives for the 2013 OHIP participants centered on the following
targets: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TD NOWRAP VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000; padding-right:8px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>&nbsp;&nbsp;</B></FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">For 2013, 65% of the OHIP award for each of the named executive officers was based on the Company performance score of
158.13%. The remainder of the OHIP award was determined by individual performance ratings based on achievement of individual performance goals and the execution of position responsibilities. The individual performance goals and weightings for each
of the named executive officers other than Mr.&nbsp;Tacka were established in February 2013 based on strategic objectives for each officer tied to our top priorities for the year. Mr.&nbsp;Tacka&#146;s individual performance goals were established
shortly after he became CFO in May 2013. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Following the close of 2013, the Committee provided the independent directors with an assessment and
scoring of Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey&#146;s performance, and Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey provided the Committee with his assessment and scoring of each named executive officer&#146;s 2013 performance and achievement relative to these performance goals. Each of our
named executive officers received a successful or higher performance rating for 2013 for achievement of position responsibilities and individual performance goals. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The individual performance goals for Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey centered on delivery of the Company&#146;s financial goals, geographic expansion and strategic leadership. Based upon our overall strong financial
results, growth in key geographies and his strategic leadership, the Committee recommended to the independent directors, and the independent directors agreed, that Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey earned an individual performance score of 200%. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Mr.&nbsp;Tacka, our Senior Vice President and Chief Financial Officer, had individual performance goals that included seamless transition of the CFO role
and due diligence regarding potential business development opportunities. Based upon Mr.&nbsp;Tacka&#146;s successful transition of the CFO position and support of our business development opportunities, Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey recommended, and the
Committee agreed, that Mr.&nbsp;Tacka earned an individual performance score of 140%. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The individual performance goals for Mr.&nbsp;Alfonso,
who held the titles of CFO, Executive Vice President and Chief Administrative Officer during fiscal year 2013 prior to becoming our President, International, in May 2013, included business development across geographic regions and leadership of our
international businesses. Based upon Mr.&nbsp;Alfonso&#146;s success in business development and leadership of our international businesses, Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey recommended, and the Committee agreed, that Mr.&nbsp;Alfonso earned an individual
performance score of 175%. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">For Ms.&nbsp;Buck, our President, North America, and until May&nbsp;13, 2013, our Senior Vice President, Chief
Growth Officer<I>, </I>the individual performance goals centered on delivering the North America financial plan, innovative growth and marketplace objectives. Based upon Ms.&nbsp;Buck&#146;s delivery of solid financial results in North America as
well as innovative growth and marketplace gains<I>,</I> </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">54 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">
<I></I>Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey recommended, and the Committee agreed, that Ms.&nbsp;Buck earned an individual performance score of 175%. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The individual performance goals for Mr.&nbsp;O&#146;Day, our Senior Vice President, Chief Supply Chain Officer, and until May&nbsp;13, 2013, our Senior Vice President, Global Operations, included focus
on sourcing expansion in the Asia market and operational support for strategic innovations. Based upon Mr.&nbsp;O&#146;Day&#146;s success regarding sourcing expansion in the Asia market and delivery of operational support for strategic
innovation<I>, </I>Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey recommended, and the Committee agreed, that Mr.&nbsp;O&#146;Day earned an individual performance score of 150%. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">For Ms.&nbsp;Turner, our Senior Vice President, General Counsel and Secretary, the individual performance goals centered on expansion of legal team expertise to support our global growth and enhancement
of corporate governance. Based upon Ms.&nbsp;Turner&#146;s success in developing capabilities to support our global operations and enhancement of corporate governance, Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey recommended, and the Committee agreed, that Ms.&nbsp;Turner
earned an individual performance score of 150%. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Based upon a 65% weight for the Company financial score of 158.13% of target and a 35% weight

</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">See Column&nbsp;(g) of the Summary Compensation Table for information relating to the amount of OHIP payments made to the named
executive officers. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>What are the elements of the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">long-term</FONT> incentive program? </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">We use awards of PSUs, stock options and Restricted Stock Units, or RSUs, to provide <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">long-term</FONT> incentive
compensation that aligns the interests of our executives with our stockholders. These awards are based on provisions of the Incentive Plan. The Committee customarily awards <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">long-term</FONT> incentive grants,
including stock options, to executive officers, other senior executives and key managerial employees in February of each year, following the release of fourth quarter and annual financial results. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">55 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px;padding-bottom:0px; "><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Committee, and the independent directors in the case of our CEO, determines the
value of <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">long-term</FONT> incentive awards made to an executive officer by comparing the executive officer&#146;s target total direct compensation (the sum of base salary, target OHIP award and the value of the
target <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">long-term</FONT> incentive award) to the 50</FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1"><SUP STYLE="vertical-align:baseline; position:relative; bottom:.8ex">th</SUP></FONT><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"> percentile level of target total direct compensation of his or her counterparts in the Compensation Peer Group and survey composite data. The target award percentages approved in February&nbsp;2013 (and
April 2013 for Mr.&nbsp;Tacka), expressed as a percentage of base salary, were: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px;padding-bottom:0px; "><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In determining the value of the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">long-term</FONT> incentive awards,
the Committee values PSUs using the average of the daily closing prices of the Company&#146;s Common Stock in the December preceding the start of the performance cycle. The Committee values RSUs using the closing price of our Common Stock on the New
York Stock Exchange, or NYSE, on the date of the award and values stock options using the value of the stock options at the date of grant as determined for financial reporting purposes (the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Black-Scholes</FONT>
value). Overall, after taking into account the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">long-term</FONT> incentive awards made in 2013, the target total direct compensation of our named executive officers was generally between the 20</FONT><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1"><SUP STYLE="vertical-align:baseline; position:relative; bottom:.8ex">th</SUP></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"> and 60</FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1"><SUP
STYLE="vertical-align:baseline; position:relative; bottom:.8ex">th </SUP></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">percentiles of total direct compensation for the comparable positions in the Compensation Peer Group and survey
composite data<B>.</B> </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>How are PSU awards structured? What performance goals are used? What were the results at <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">year-end</FONT> 2013? </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">PSUs are granted to those executive officers and other senior executives in a position
to affect the Company&#146;s <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">long-term</FONT> results. At the start of each <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">three-year</FONT> cycle, a contingent target number of PSUs is established for each executive. This target
is expressed as a percentage of the executive&#146;s annual base salary and determined as part of a total compensation package based on the applicable Compensation Peer Group and survey composite benchmarks. The PSU award generally represents
approximately <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">one-half</FONT> of the recipient&#146;s <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">long-term</FONT> incentive compensation target award. Dividends are not paid on PSU awards during the three-year performance
cycle. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The performance objectives for the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">2011-2013</FONT> performance cycle awarded in 2011 were based upon
the following metrics: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Three-year relative TSR versus the Financial Peer Group (described below); </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:2px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Annual (as opposed to three-year) growth in adjusted <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">earnings&nbsp;per&nbsp;share-diluted</FONT> measured against an
internal target for each year of the three-year performance cycle. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">56 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Committee selected these metrics to measure performance against internal targets aligned with our
stockholders&#146; interests and investment returns offered by our peer companies. Based on input from Mercer, the Committee selected 13 food, beverage and consumer products companies with a median revenue of $7.6&nbsp;billion for use in assessing
our Company&#146;s <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">2011-2013</FONT> TSR against the food and beverage industry. We refer to these companies as our Financial Peer Group. The Financial Peer Group is a high-performing group of companies with whom we
compete for investors in the food and beverage industry. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Companies included in the 13-member 2011 Financial Peer Group were: </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TD VALIGN="bottom" WIDTH="2%"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="47%"></TD></TR>


<TR>
<TD VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE="margin-left:1.00em; text-indent:-1.00em"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Campbell Soup Company</FONT></P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD>

<TD VALIGN="bottom"></TD></TR>
</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Due to privatization of the Del&nbsp;Monte Foods Company in 2011, the spin-offs by Kraft Foods Inc. and Sara Lee
Corporation in 2012, and privatization of H. J. Heinz during 2013, the Committee removed these companies from the Financial Peer Group for the purpose of measuring three-year relative TSR for the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">2011-2013</FONT>
performance cycle and, to the extent applicable, the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">2012-2014</FONT> and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">2013-2015</FONT> performance cycles. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Committee approves the annual adjusted <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">earnings&nbsp;per&nbsp;share-diluted</FONT> target for each year of the three-year performance cycle at the beginning of the
performance year. The annual component allows the Committee to establish performance targets that reflect current business conditions, thus strengthening the link between pay and performance for each year of the
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">three-year</FONT> cycle. Payment of any amounts earned, including amounts based on the annual performance goals, will be made in shares of our Common Stock at the conclusion of the
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">three-year</FONT> performance cycle. The maximum award for any participant in a performance cycle is 250% of the contingent target award. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Targets for the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">2011-2013</FONT> performance cycle and the Company&#146;s TSR and financial performance during the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">2011-2013</FONT>
performance cycle were as follows: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

excluding the non-service related pension costs was $2.83. For 2012 and 2013, the target and actual adjusted <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">earnings&nbsp;per&nbsp;share-diluted</FONT> presented above excluded the non-service related pension cost.

<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">At the conclusion of each <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">three-year</FONT> and annual performance period, the Committee reviews the level of
performance achieved and the percentage, if any, of the applicable portion of the target number of PSUs earned. In determining the final performance cycle score, negative adjustments may be made by the Committee to the Company&#146;s performance
score to take into account extraordinary or unusual items occurring during the period. No adjustments were made in determining the 216.22% performance score or the number of PSUs earned by our named executive officers for the <FONT

</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Committee introduced a target for organic net sales growth outside of the United States and Canada as a performance
metric for the 2012-2014 performance cycle, and continued it in the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">2013-2015</FONT> performance cycle, in recognition of our strategic initiatives emphasizing the contributions that international sales growth can
make to our long-term success. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">58 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The actual Company results for 2013 of $3.72 of adjusted
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">earnings&nbsp;per&nbsp;share-diluted</FONT> reflected a 14.8% increase from 2012 and exceeded the 2013 target of $3.61. As a result, 11.16% of the final award was earned for this metric in the <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">2012-2014</FONT> and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">2013-2015</FONT> performance cycles. These PSUs will be paid at the end of each of the applicable <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">three-year</FONT> performance cycles
to participating executives who are entitled to payouts under the terms of the program. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">See Column&nbsp;(e) of the Summary Compensation Table
on page&nbsp;64, Columns&nbsp;(f) through&nbsp;(h) of the Grants of <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Plan-Based</FONT> Awards table on page&nbsp;69, Columns&nbsp;(i) and&nbsp;(j) of the Outstanding Equity Awards table on page&nbsp;71 and
Columns&nbsp;(d) and&nbsp;(e) of the Option Exercises and Stock Vested table on page&nbsp;73 for more information about PSUs awarded to the named executive officers. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>How are stock options used within the Company&#146;s <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">long-term</FONT> incentive program? What process is followed in the granting of stock options? </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Stock options are an important element of our long-term incentive program, enabling us to align the interests of executive officers with those of
stockholders. In general, stock options are awarded annually to the Company&#146;s senior executive group as well as to other key managerial employees. Stock options entitle the holder to purchase a fixed number of shares of Common Stock at a set
price during a specified period of time. The right to exercise the options is subject to a vesting schedule. Because stock options vest over time and only have value if the price of our Common Stock increases, they encourage efforts to enhance <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">long-term</FONT> stockholder value. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Committee sets guidelines for the value of stock options to be awarded
based on competitive compensation data. In 2013, the target number of stock options awarded to each executive officer was determined by multiplying the executive officer&#146;s base salary by one-half of his or her target long-term incentive award
percentage divided by the Black-Scholes value of each option on the grant date. The Black-Scholes option-pricing model is described in Note&nbsp;17 to the Consolidated Financial Statements contained in the 2013 Annual Report to Stockholders that
accompanies this proxy statement. The actual number of options awarded may vary from the target level based on an executive officer&#146;s individual performance evaluation. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Stock options awarded in 2013 vest in equal increments over four years and have a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">ten-year</FONT> term. As required by the stockholder-approved Incentive Plan, the options
have an exercise price equal to the closing market price of the Common Stock on the NYSE on the date of the award. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">To ensure flexibility in
providing awards for recruitment, retention, performance recognition or in conjunction with a promotion, the Committee is authorized under the Incentive Plan to establish a stock option pool, an RSU pool and a separate CEO discretionary equity pool
for use by our CEO for such purposes. The pools are available for approximately 12 months from the date created. The Committee determines whether to establish any or all of these three pools annually. Options and RSUs remaining in any pool at the
end of the period do not carry over to pools established for a subsequent period. The CEO may not make discretionary awards from any pool to the Company&#146;s executive officers. Stock option and RSU awards from the CEO pools as well as awards from
the CEO discretionary equity pool are made monthly according to an annually <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pre-determined</FONT> schedule. The exercise price for the options is based on the closing price of our Common Stock on the date of the
award. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">See Column&nbsp;(f) of the Summary Compensation Table, Columns&nbsp;(j) through (l)&nbsp;of the Grants of <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Plan-Based</FONT> Awards table, Columns&nbsp;(b) through (f)&nbsp;of the Outstanding Equity Awards table and Columns&nbsp;(b) and (c)&nbsp;of the Option Exercises and Stock Vested table for more information on stock
options awarded to the named executive officers. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">59 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>How are RSUs used within the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">long-term</FONT> incentive program?
</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Committee awards RSUs to executive officers and other senior executives from time to time as special incentives. RSUs also are
awarded by the Committee to replace compensation forfeited by <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">newly-hired</FONT> executive officers and by the CEO to employees other than executive officers from the RSU pool described previously. In 2013, the
Committee did not make any RSU awards to any of the named executive officers. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>What retirement benefits are provided to the executive
officers? </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Based on their date of hire, executive officers participate in the same defined benefit pension and defined contribution 401(k)
plans as do other salaried employees of the Company. IRC regulations do not permit the Company to use base salary and other compensation paid above certain limits to determine the benefits earned by the executive officers under <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">tax-qualified</FONT> plans. The Company maintains a defined benefit Supplemental Executive Retirement Plan, or DB&nbsp;SERP, a defined contribution Supplemental Executive Retirement Plan, or DC&nbsp;SERP, a defined benefit
Compensation Limit Replacement Plan, or CLRP, and a Deferred Compensation Plan to provide these and additional benefits that are comparable to those offered by our competitors. Under the provisions of the Deferred Compensation Plan, our named
executive officers may elect to defer payments from the DB&nbsp;SERP, DC&nbsp;SERP, CLRP, the OHIP, and PSU and RSU awards, but not stock options. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The DB&nbsp;SERP was closed to new participants in 2006. No new participants have been or will be added to the DB&nbsp;SERP. Executive officers and Senior Vice Presidents reporting to the CEO not eligible
for the DB&nbsp;SERP are considered by the Committee for participation in the DC&nbsp;SERP. In comparison, the DC&nbsp;SERP typically yields a lower benefit than the DB&nbsp;SERP upon retirement. Executive officers eligible for the Company&#146;s
qualified defined benefit pension plan who are not eligible for the DB SERP participate in the CLRP. The Company believes that the DB&nbsp;SERP, DC&nbsp;SERP, CLRP and Deferred Compensation Plan help, in the aggregate, to attract and retain
executive talent, as similar plans are often components of the executive compensation programs within our Compensation Peer Group. The DC&nbsp;SERP was established as part of our Deferred Compensation Plan and is not a separate plan. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">See the Pension Benefits table and accompanying narrative beginning on page&nbsp;74 and the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Non-Qualified</FONT>
Deferred Compensation table and accompanying narrative beginning on page&nbsp;76 for more information regarding the DB&nbsp;SERP, DC&nbsp;SERP, CLRP and other retirement benefits. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>What role do executive perquisites play in the total compensation package for the executive officers? </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Executive perquisites are kept by the Committee to a minimal level relative to an executive officer&#146;s total compensation and do not play a significant role in our executive compensation program. The
perquisites that we do provide, personal use of Company aircraft, security services for our CEO, and financial and tax counseling, are of the type that we believe promote the efficiency, effectiveness and focus of our executive officers in the
performance of their duties. See the footnotes to Column&nbsp;(i) of the Summary Compensation Table for information regarding the perquisites received by our named executive officers. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Our CEO and the other named executive officers are eligible to participate in our Gift Matching Program on the same basis as other employees, retirees or their spouses. Through the Gift Matching Program,
we match contributions made to one or more accredited colleges or </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">60 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">
universities on a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">dollar-for-dollar</FONT></FONT> basis up to a maximum aggregate contribution of $5,000 per employee annually.
These matching contributions are not considered compensation and are not included in Column&nbsp;(i) of the Summary Compensation Table. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Has the Company implemented provisions designed to protect the Company, such as conditioning compensation on restrictive covenants? </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In 2008, the Company initiated a program for executive officers conditioning the receiving of PSUs and other
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">long-term</FONT> incentive awards and, for new executive officers, also as a condition of their employment, on the execution of an agreement designed to protect the Company with certain restrictive covenants. In
2013, the Company expanded the program to include certain employees along with executive officers. As is the case with the executive officers, these employees are required to enter into the Employee Confidentiality and Restrictive Covenant
Agreement, or ECRCA, as a condition of the receipt of long-term incentive awards, and, for new employees, also as a condition of employment. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The terms of the ECRCA prohibit the executive officer or employee from misusing or disclosing the Company&#146;s confidential information, competing with
the Company in specific categories for a period of 12 months following separation from employment, recruiting or soliciting the Company&#146;s employees, or disparaging the Company&#146;s reputation in any way. For those officers or employees based
outside the U.S., the restrictive covenants and terms may be modified to comply with local laws. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Failure to comply with the provisions of the
ECRCA may result in cancellation of the unvested portion of PSU and RSU awards, cancellation of any unexercised stock options and a requirement for repayment of amounts received from equity awards during the last year of employment as well as any
amounts received from the DB&nbsp;SERP or DC&nbsp;SERP. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Has the Company entered into any employment agreements with or does the Company
provide severance or Change in Control plans for its executive officers? </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">We have not entered into employment agreements with any named
executive officer, except for Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey, our CEO. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">During 2012, we entered into an employment agreement with Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey. The
Committee and independent members of the Board determined that doing so was appropriate since we had entered into an employment agreement with Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey&#146;s predecessor and believed we would have been required to enter into an employment
agreement with any individual recruited to become our CEO from another company. Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey&#146;s employment agreement does not include a golden parachute excise tax gross-up feature. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">All of the named executive officers participate in our Executive Benefits Protection Plan (Group 3A), or EBPP&nbsp;3A. The EBPP&nbsp;3A is intended to help us attract and retain qualified management
employees and maintain a stable work environment in the event of activity that could potentially result in a Change in Control. The severance protection provided under EBPP&nbsp;3A upon a Change in Control is a &#147;double trigger.&#148; The terms
of the plan generally provide that a covered executive officer whose employment with the Company terminates in qualifying circumstances within two years after a Change in Control of the Company is entitled to certain severance payments and benefits.
The EBPP&nbsp;3A also provides severance benefits in the event of involuntary termination without Cause unrelated to a Change in Control or voluntary termination for Good Reason within two years after election of a new CEO. Cause and Good Reason are
defined in the EBPP&nbsp;3A. The EBPP&nbsp;3A does not include a golden parachute excise tax <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">gross-up</FONT> feature. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">61 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">See the discussion beginning on page&nbsp;78 for information regarding the EBPP&nbsp;3A and payments that
would be due to our named executive officers under that plan in the event of an applicable termination of employment or a Change in Control, as defined in the EBPP&nbsp;3A. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Do we require our executive officers to hold Company stock? </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Company believes that
requiring executive officers to hold significant amounts of our Common Stock strengthens the alignment of the executive officers with the interest of stockholders and promotes achievement of <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">long-term</FONT> business
objectives. Our executive stock ownership policy has been in place for more than 20 years. Ownership requirements are reviewed annually by Mercer and were updated in 2008 to better align with external market comparisons provided by Mercer.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Executives with stock ownership requirements have five years from their initial election to their position to accumulate and hold the minimum
number of shares required. For purposes of this requirement, &#147;shares&#148; include shares of our Common Stock that are owned by the executive, unvested <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">time-based</FONT> RSUs, PSUs earned for the annual segments
of open performance cycles, as well as vested RSUs and PSUs that have been deferred by the executive as common stock units under our Deferred Compensation Plan. It is anticipated that executives will hold a significant number of the shares earned
from PSU and RSU awards and the exercise of stock options to satisfy their obligations. Currently, minimum stockholding requirements for executive officers and other executives range from one to five times base salary, as described in the table
below. The dollar value of shares which must be acquired and held equals a multiple of the individual executive&#146;s base salary. Stock holding requirements are updated whenever a change in base salary occurs. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

notification letter to the executive, with a copy to the CEO, and a requirement that future stock option exercises and PSU payments be settled by retaining at least 50% of the shares of Common Stock received until the minimum ownership level is
attained. The Committee receives an annual summary of each individual executive&#146;s ownership status to monitor compliance. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">As of
February&nbsp;28, 2014, the record date for the annual meeting, all of the named executive officers exceeded their ownership requirements. </FONT></P>

<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1">(3)</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1">Column&nbsp;(e) shows the grant date fair value of contingent target PSU awards granted to the named executive officers for the years indicated and does not reflect the
value of shares actually received or which may be received in the future with respect to such awards. The amount for 2013 shown in Column&nbsp;(e)&nbsp;includes the aggregate grant date fair value of contingent target PSU awards for the <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">2013-2015</FONT> performance cycle, the 2013 adjusted earnings <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">per&nbsp;share-diluted</FONT> component of the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">2012-2014</FONT> performance cycle, and, with
the exception of Ms.&nbsp;Turner, the 2013 adjusted <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">earnings&nbsp;per&nbsp;share-diluted</FONT> component of the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">2011-2013</FONT> performance cycle. With the exception of
Mr.&nbsp;Tacka, Column&nbsp;(e) reflects the grant date fair value of the PSUs awarded to each named executive officer in March&nbsp;2013. The amount listed in Column&nbsp;(e) for Mr.&nbsp;Tacka includes the grant date fair value of contingent
target PSU awards for the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">2013-2015</FONT> performance cycle granted in March&nbsp;2013 and in May&nbsp;2013 when he was promoted to Senior Vice President, Chief Financial Officer. </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1">The number of options awarded to each named executive officer on February&nbsp;19,&nbsp;2013, was targeted as <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">one-half</FONT> of the
executive&#146;s <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">long-term</FONT> incentive target percentage times his or her 2013 base salary divided by the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Black-Scholes</FONT> value of $14.42 for each option. The <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Black-Scholes</FONT> value is based on the $81.73 exercise price for these options determined as the closing price of the Company&#146;s Common Stock on the award date, February&nbsp;19,&nbsp;2013. The actual number of
options awarded varied from the target level based on the executive&#146;s performance evaluation for 2013. The options awarded to Mr.&nbsp;Tacka on July&nbsp;10, 2013, had an exercise price per share of $90.71 and a
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Black-Scholes</FONT> value of $18.01 for each option. </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1">All options awarded by the Company have a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">ten-year</FONT> term and vest in 25% increments over four years. Unvested options are
forfeited if the executive terminates his or her employment, unless the termination is due to the executive&#146;s death, disability or retirement, in which case (i)&nbsp;options granted prior to April&nbsp;28,&nbsp;2011, continue to vest and are
exercisable for five years following termination, and (ii)&nbsp;options granted on or after April&nbsp;28,&nbsp;2011, vest immediately and are exercisable for three or five years following termination (depending on the terms and conditions of the
grant). Options granted in the year of retirement are prorated based upon the number of full calendar months worked in that year. In the event of a Change in Control, options granted prior to April&nbsp;28,&nbsp;2011, automatically vest upon the
Change in Control and options granted on or after April&nbsp;28,&nbsp;2011, automatically vest unless a qualifying replacement award remains outstanding after the Change in Control, in which case options will vest in accordance with the original
vesting schedule. Within the two-year period following a Change in Control, options will vest immediately if the executive&#146;s employment is terminated without Cause or the executive resigns for Good Reason, both as defined in the EBPP&nbsp;3A.
No option may be exercised later than the option expiration date. More information regarding stock options and the 2013 awards can be found in the Compensation Discussion and Analysis and the Outstanding Equity Awards table below.
</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1">(1)</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1">Columns&nbsp;(b) through&nbsp;(f) present information about stock options awarded to each named executive officer under the Incentive Plan. Each option
award vests in increments of 25% on each of the first four anniversaries of the grant date and are subject to earlier vesting in the event of a Change in Control for awards granted prior to April&nbsp;28,&nbsp;2011. Awards granted on or after
April&nbsp;28,&nbsp;2011, will vest earlier if a qualifying replacement award is not outstanding after the Change in Control. Generally, </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">71 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">


<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1">
upon termination of employment, vested options must be exercised and unvested options are cancelled, except in the case of retirement, death or disability, in which case the options
(i)&nbsp;continue to vest as scheduled (in the case of awards granted prior to April&nbsp;28,&nbsp;2011) or (ii)&nbsp;vest immediately (in the case of awards granted on or after April&nbsp;28,&nbsp;2011). Participants whose employment terminates due
to retirement, death or disability may exercise vested options for up to three or five years (based on the terms and conditions of the grant) after termination of employment. Options granted in the year of retirement are prorated based upon the
number of full calendar months worked in that year. If termination occurs within two years after a Change in Control for any reason other than for Cause or by the executive without Good Reason (as defined in the EBPP&nbsp;3A), any replacement awards
relating to options granted on or after April&nbsp;28,&nbsp;2011, will vest in full and may be exercised for one year after termination. If a named executive officer is under age 55 (and for options granted on or after April&nbsp;28,&nbsp;2011, has
completed less than five years of continuous service), and his or her employment is terminated for reasons other than for Cause or by the executive without Good Reason (as defined in the EBPP&nbsp;3A), the executive will be eligible to exercise all
vested stock options and a prorated portion of his or her unvested stock options held on the date of separation from service for a period of 120 days following separation. No option may be exercised after its expiration date.
</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1">(2)</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1">Options listed in Column&nbsp;(b) are vested and may be exercised by the executive at any time subject to the terms of the stock option. </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>

 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">73 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc634600_20"></A>Pension Benefits </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Each of the named executive officers, with the exception of Mr.&nbsp;O&#146;Day and Ms.&nbsp;Turner, is a participant in our <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">tax-qualified</FONT> defined benefit pension
plan and is fully vested in his or her benefit under that plan. Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey, Mr.&nbsp;Tacka and Ms.&nbsp;Buck are eligible to participate in our <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-qualified</FONT> DB&nbsp;SERP. No benefit is payable under the
DB&nbsp;SERP if the executive officer terminates employment prior to age 55 or if he or she does not have five years of service with the Company. As of December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2013, Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey and Mr.&nbsp;Tacka had attained age 55 with five
years of service. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The combination of the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">tax-qualified</FONT> defined benefit pension and DB&nbsp;SERP plans
were designed to provide a benefit upon retirement at or after reaching age 60 based on a joint and survivor annuity equal to 55% of final average compensation for an executive with 15 or more years of service (reduced pro rata for each year of
service under 15). Effective January&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2007, the benefit payable under the DB&nbsp;SERP to an executive who was age 50 or over as of January&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2007, was reduced by 10%, and the benefit payable to an executive who had not
attained age 50 as of January&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2007, was reduced by 20%. The benefit payable to Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey was reduced by 10% and the benefit payable to Ms.&nbsp;Buck was reduced by 20%. In connection with his promotion to Senior Vice President
and Chief Financial Officer in May 2013, a 2007 arrangement exempting Mr.&nbsp;Tacka&#146;s benefit from the 10% reduction was extended through Mr.&nbsp;Tacka&#146;s retirement. The exemption had been scheduled to expire in September 2013.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Final average compensation is calculated as the sum of (i)&nbsp;the average of the highest three calendar years of base salary paid over the
last five years of employment with the Company and (ii)&nbsp;the average of the highest three annual incentive program awards for the last five years of employment with the Company, whether paid or deferred. The benefit accrued under the
DB&nbsp;SERP is payable upon retirement as a lump sum, a life annuity with 50% benefit continuation to the participant&#146;s surviving spouse, or payment may be deferred in accordance with the provisions of the Company&#146;s Deferred Compensation
Plan. The lump sum is equal to the actuarial present value of the joint and survivor pension earned, reduced by the lump sum value of the benefits to be paid under the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">tax-qualified</FONT> defined benefit pension
plan and the value of the executive&#146;s Social Security benefits. If the executive terminates employment after age 55 but before age 60, the benefit is reduced for early retirement at a rate of 5%&nbsp;per year for the period until the executive
would have turned 60. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The defined benefit Compensation Limit Replacement Plan, or CLRP, provides eligible participants the defined benefit he
or she would have earned under our <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">tax-qualified</FONT> defined benefit pension plan were it not for the legal limitation on compensation used to determine benefits. An executive who is a participant in the
DB&nbsp;SERP is not eligible to participate in the CLRP unless he or she (i)&nbsp;ceases to be designated by the Committee as eligible to participate in the DB&nbsp;SERP prior to his or her termination of employment with the Company or (ii)&nbsp;has
his or her employment involuntarily terminated by the Company other than for Cause prior to vesting in the DB&nbsp;SERP. Named executive officers meeting these criteria become eligible to participate in the CLRP and receive a benefit for all years
in which they would have been a participant of the CLRP had they not been designated by the Committee to be eligible for the DB&nbsp;SERP. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Executives who are eligible for both the DC&nbsp;SERP (described under <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Non-Qualified</FONT> Deferred Compensation below)
and the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">tax-qualified</FONT> defined benefit pension plan receive an additional credit under the CLRP equal to 3% of eligible earnings less the IRS annual limitation on compensation. Mr.&nbsp;Alfonso is the only
named executive officer eligible for the CLRP. Upon separation, benefits under the CLRP are payable in a single lump sum or may be deferred into the Deferred Compensation Plan. A participant is eligible for his or her CLRP benefit upon separation
</FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">74 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">
from service (subject to the provisions of Section&nbsp;409A of the IRC) after five years of service or attaining age 55 (unless the participant is terminated for Cause). Payment is also made to
the estate of a participant who dies prior to separation from service. Participants who become disabled are 100% vested in their benefit and continue to accrue additional benefits for up to two additional years. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The following table and explanatory footnotes provide information regarding the present value of benefits accrued under the <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">tax-qualified</FONT> defined benefit pension plan, as applicable, and the DB&nbsp;SERP or CLRP for each named executive officer as of December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2013. The amounts shown for the DB&nbsp;SERP reflect the
reduction for the present value of the benefits under the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">tax-qualified</FONT> defined benefit pension plan and Social Security benefits. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT
