 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">75 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc634600_21"></A><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Non-Qualified</FONT> Deferred Compensation
</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Our named executive officers are eligible to participate in The Hershey Company Deferred Compensation Plan. The Deferred Compensation
Plan is a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-qualified,</FONT> <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-funded</FONT> plan that permits participants to defer compensation that would otherwise be paid to them currently. The Deferred Compensation Plan
is intended to secure the goodwill and loyalty of participants by enabling them to defer compensation when the participants deem it beneficial to do so and by providing a vehicle for the Company to provide, on a
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-qualified</FONT> basis, contributions that could not be made on the participants&#146; behalf to the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">tax-qualified</FONT> 401(k). The Company credits the Deferred Compensation
Plan with a specified percentage of compensation for executive officers participating in the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-qualified</FONT> DC&nbsp;SERP. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Our named executive officers may elect to defer payments to be received from the DB&nbsp;SERP, DC&nbsp;SERP, CLRP, and the OHIP as well as PSU and RSU awards, but not stock options. Amounts deferred are
fully vested and are credited to the individual&#146;s account under the Deferred Compensation Plan. Participants elect to receive payment at termination of employment or some other future date. DB&nbsp;SERP and CLRP payments designated for deferral
into the Deferred Compensation Plan are not credited as earned but are credited in full upon the participant&#146;s retirement. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Payments are
distributed in a lump sum or in annual installments for up to 15 years. All amounts are payable in a lump sum following a Change in Control. All elections and payments under the Deferred Compensation Plan are subject to compliance with
Section&nbsp;409A of the IRC which may limit elections and require a delay in payment of benefits in certain circumstances. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">While deferred,
amounts are credited with notional earnings as if they were invested by the participant in one or more investment options offered by the Deferred Compensation Plan. The investment options under the Deferred Compensation Plan consist of investment in
a deferred common stock unit account that we value according to the performance of our Common Stock (for awards paid in stock) or in mutual funds or other investments available to participants in our 401(k) (for awards paid in cash). The
participants&#146; accounts under the Deferred Compensation Plan fluctuate daily, depending upon performance of the investment options elected. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Effective January&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2007, we began crediting the deferred compensation accounts of all employees, including the named executive officers, with
the amount of employer matching contributions that exceed the limits established by the IRS for contribution to the 401(k). These amounts are credited in the first quarter of the year after they are earned. As shown in the footnotes to the Summary
Compensation Table beginning on page&nbsp;64, these amounts are designated as &#147;Supplemental 401(k) Match&#148; and are included as &#147;All Other Compensation&#148; in the year earned. These amounts also are included in Column&nbsp;(c) of the <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Non-Qualified</FONT> Deferred Compensation table in the year earned. With the exception of Ms.&nbsp;Turner, all of the named executive officers are fully vested in the Supplemental 401(k) Match credits presented and will
be paid at a future date or at termination of employment, as elected by the officer subject to the provisions of Section&nbsp;409A of the IRC. Ms.&nbsp;Turner will vest in this benefit upon completion of two years of employment. If vested, she will
receive payment for this benefit at termination of employment subject to the provisions of Section&nbsp;409A of the IRC. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Effective
January&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2007, we began crediting the deferred compensation accounts of all employees hired on or after January&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2007, including eligible named executive officers, with the amount of Core Retirement Contributions that exceed
the limits established by the IRS for contribution to the 401(k). These amounts are credited in the first quarter of the year after they are earned. As shown in the footnotes to the Summary Compensation Table, these amounts are
</FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">76 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">
designated as &#147;Supplemental Core Retirement Contribution&#148; and are included as &#147;All Other Compensation&#148; in the year earned. These amounts also are included in Column&nbsp;(c)
of the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Non-Qualified</FONT> Deferred Compensation table in the year earned. Mr.&nbsp;O&#146;Day and Ms.&nbsp;Turner are eligible for a Supplemental Core Retirement Contribution credit for 2013. Mr.&nbsp;O&#146;Day is
fully vested in this benefit and will receive payment for this benefit at termination of employment subject to the provisions of Section&nbsp;409A of the IRC. Ms.&nbsp;Turner will vest in this benefit upon completion of two years of employment. If
vested, she will receive payment for this benefit at termination of employment subject to the provisions of Section&nbsp;409A of the IRC. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Mr.&nbsp;Alfonso, Mr.&nbsp;O&#146;Day and Ms.&nbsp;Turner are eligible to participate in our DC&nbsp;SERP, a part of the Deferred Compensation Plan. The
DC&nbsp;SERP provides annual allocations to the Deferred Compensation Plan equal to a percentage of compensation determined by the Committee in its sole discretion. In order to receive the annual DC&nbsp;SERP allocation, an executive officer must
(i)&nbsp;defer in the 401(k) the maximum amount allowed by the Company or IRS and (ii)&nbsp;be employed on the last day of the plan year unless the executive officer terminates employment after age 55 and completion of five years of continuous
employment preceding termination, dies or becomes disabled. After completing five years of service with the Company, an executive officer is vested in 10% increments based on his or her age. An executive age&nbsp;46 with five years of service is 10%
vested and an executive age 55 with five years of service is 100% vested. Mr.&nbsp;Alfonso&#146;s, Mr.&nbsp;O&#146;Day&#146;s and Ms.&nbsp;Turner&#146;s annual DC&nbsp;SERP allocation is equal to 12.5% of base salary and OHIP award for the calendar
year, whether paid or deferred. Mr.&nbsp;Alfonso and Mr.&nbsp;O&#146;Day are 100% vested in their DC&nbsp;SERP benefit. Ms.&nbsp;Turner is not vested in any portion of her DC&nbsp;SERP benefit. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The following table and explanatory footnotes provide information relating to the activity in the Deferred Compensation Plan accounts of the named
executive officers during 2013 and the aggregate balance of the accounts as of December&nbsp;31, 2013. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Non-Qualified</FONT> Deferred Compensation </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>2013 </B></FONT></P>

</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc634600_22"></A>Potential Payments Upon Termination or Change in Control </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">We maintain plans covering our executive officers that will require us to provide incremental compensation in the event of involuntary termination of
employment or a Change in Control, provided certain conditions are met. We describe these obligations below. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>Overview </I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Company entered into an employment agreement with Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey, our President and CEO in August 2012, which provides for Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey&#146;s
continued employment as President and CEO and as a member of the Board of Directors. The employment agreement does not have a specified term; Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey&#146;s employment is on an at-will basis. In the event Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey&#146;s employment
is terminated by the Company without Cause or he resigns for Good Reason (in each case as defined in the employment agreement), Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey will be entitled to certain severance benefits. In the event of his termination after a Change in
Control, Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey will be eligible to receive benefits under the EBPP&nbsp;3A. He is not entitled to an excise tax gross-up. The employment agreement subjects Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey to certain non-competition and non-solicitation covenants under
the ECRCA (as described below) and to compensation recovery (clawback) to the extent required by applicable law and regulations. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Our other
named executive officers also participate in the EBPP&nbsp;3A. The EBPP&nbsp;3A is intended to help us attract and retain qualified executive employees and maintain a stable work environment by making a provision for the protection of covered
executives in connection with a Change in Control of Hershey or termination of employment under certain circumstances. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">78 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Each of our named executive officers was required to sign an Employee Confidentiality and Restrictive
Covenant Agreement, or ECRCA, as a condition to receiving <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">long-term</FONT> incentive compensation awards such as stock options and PSUs. The ECRCA obligates the executive officer to not disclose or misuse our
confidential and proprietary information or, for a period of 12 months following termination, carry on any activities that compete with our business. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Termination of employment and a Change in Control also impact PSUs, RSUs and stock option awards we have made, as well as benefits payable under our employee benefit plans. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The following narrative takes each termination of employment situation &#150; voluntary resignation, termination for Cause (as defined in the
EBPP&nbsp;3A), death, disability, retirement, termination without Cause, and resignation for Good Reason (as defined in the EBPP&nbsp;3A) &#150; and a Change in Control of the Company, and it describes the additional amounts, if any, that the
Company would pay or provide to Messrs.&nbsp;Bilbrey, Tacka, Alfonso, and O&#146;Day,&nbsp;Ms.&nbsp;Buck and Ms.&nbsp;Turner, or their beneficiaries as a result. The narrative below and the amounts shown reflect certain assumptions we have made in
accordance with SEC rules. We have assumed that the termination of employment or Change in Control occurred on December&nbsp;31, 2013, and that the value of a share of our Common Stock on that day was $97.23, the closing price on the NYSE on
December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2013. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In addition, in keeping with SEC rules, the following narrative and amounts do not include payments and benefits
which are not enhanced by a qualifying termination of employment or Change in Control. These payments and benefits include: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Benefits accrued under the Company&#146;s <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">broad-based,</FONT> <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">tax-qualified</FONT>
401(k) and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">tax-qualified</FONT> defined benefit pension plan; </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:2px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>

<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Vested benefits accrued under the DB&nbsp;SERP, CLRP and account balances held under the Deferred Compensation Plan as previously described beginning
on pages&nbsp;74 and 76; and </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:2px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Stock options which have vested and become exercisable prior to termination of employment or Change in Control. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The payments and benefits described in the five bullet points above are referred to in the following discussion as the executive officer&#146;s
&#147;vested benefits.&#148; </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>Voluntary Resignation (other than a Resignation for Good Reason) </I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">We are not obligated to pay amounts over and above vested benefits to a named executive officer who voluntarily resigns. Vested stock options may not be
exercised after the named executive officer&#146;s resignation date unless the officer is age 55 or older and, in certain instances, has met minimum service requirements as described in Treatment of Stock Options upon Retirement, Death or Disability
below. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>Termination for Cause </I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">If we terminate a named executive officer&#146;s employment for Cause (as defined in the EBPP&nbsp;3A), we are not obligated to pay the officer any
amounts over and above the vested benefits. The named executive officer&#146;s right to exercise vested options expires upon discharge for Cause, and amounts otherwise payable under the DB&nbsp;SERP are subject to forfeiture at the Company&#146;s
discretion. In general, a discharge will be for Cause if the executive has been convicted of a felony </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">79 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">
or has engaged in gross negligence or willful misconduct in the performance of duties, material dishonesty or a material violation of Company policies, including our Code of Ethical Business
Conduct, or bad faith actions in the performance of duties not in the best interests of the Company. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>Death or Disability </I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">If an executive officer dies and has not met the vesting requirements to be eligible to receive a benefit from the DB&nbsp;SERP, no benefits are paid.
Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey and Mr.&nbsp;Tacka are fully vested in their DB&nbsp;SERP benefits as of December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2013. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">A maximum monthly <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">long-term</FONT> disability benefit of $35,000 would be provided for Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey and $25,000 for all other named executive officers in the event of <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">long-term</FONT> disability. <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Long-term</FONT> disability benefits are generally payable until age 65, but may extend for longer if disability benefits begin after age 60. <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Long-term</FONT> disability benefits are offset
by other benefits such as Social Security. The maximum amount of the monthly <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">long-term</FONT> disability payments from all sources, assuming <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">long-term</FONT> disability began on
December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2013, is set forth in the tables below. The additional lump sum DB&nbsp;SERP amount that would be payable for Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey, Mr.&nbsp;Tacka and Ms.&nbsp;Buck at age 65, attributable to vesting and benefit service credited
during the disability period for the DB&nbsp;SERP, if the executive&#146;s disability started on December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2013, is shown on the table below. Mr.&nbsp;Alfonso participates in the CLRP which provides two additional years of credit after
approval for <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">long-term</FONT> disability benefits. Mr.&nbsp;O&#146;Day and Ms.&nbsp;Turner are eligible for the Supplemental Core Retirement Contribution and would receive up to two additional years of Supplemental
Core Retirement Contribution credit after approval for <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">long-term</FONT> disability benefits. Mr.&nbsp;Alfonso, Mr.&nbsp;O&#146;Day and Ms.&nbsp;Turner participate in the DC&nbsp;SERP which provides up to two
additional years of credit after approval for <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">long-term</FONT> disability benefits. Those amounts are listed in the table below: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>Treatment of Stock Options upon Retirement, Death or Disability </I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In the event of retirement, death or disability, vested stock options remain exercisable for a period of three or five years but not later than the
option expiration date. The exercise period is based upon the terms and conditions of the individual grant. For awards granted prior to April&nbsp;28,&nbsp;2011, retirement was defined as separation after attainment of age 55. For awards granted on
or after April&nbsp;28,&nbsp;2011, retirement is defined as separation after attainment of age 55 with at least five years of continuous service. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Options awarded prior to April&nbsp;28,&nbsp;2011, that are not vested at the time of retirement, death or disability will continue to vest over the five years following termination in accordance with the
original vesting schedule established on the grant date. Options granted on or after April&nbsp;28,&nbsp;2011, that are not vested at the time of retirement, death or disability will vest in full, and the options will remain exercisable for three or
five years following termination. Options granted in the year of retirement are prorated based upon the number of full calendar months worked in that year. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The following table provides the number of unvested stock options as of December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2013, that would have become vested and remained exercisable during the three-year or five-year periods
following death or disability, or retirement, if applicable, on December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2013, and the value of those options based on the excess of the fair market value of our Common Stock on December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2013, over the option exercise
price. Messrs.&nbsp;Bilbrey, Tacka, Alfonso, and O&#146;Day were considered retirement eligible based on the provisions of all option awards on December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2013. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

considered retirement eligible for any of her unvested options because she does not have five years of continuous service. Ms.&nbsp;Turner would forfeit 46,502 stock options upon voluntary separation. </FONT></P>

<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>Treatment of RSUs upon Retirement, Death or Disability </I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Upon retirement any RSUs held by our named executive officers that are not vested are forfeited. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">A prorated portion of unvested RSUs granted prior to April&nbsp;28,&nbsp;2011, will vest upon death or disability. The prorated number of RSUs is based
upon the number of full and partial calendar months from the grant date to the date of death or disability divided by the full and partial calendar months from the grant date to the end of the restriction period, multiplied by the number of RSUs
originally granted. Unvested RSUs granted on or after April&nbsp;28,&nbsp;2011, will vest in full upon death or disability. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The following
table summarizes the unvested RSU awards that would have vested on December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2013, if the executive&#146;s employment terminated that day due to death or disability. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" COLSPAN="6" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Restricted Stock Units</B></FONT></TD>

<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>Termination without Cause; Resignation for Good Reason </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Under Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey&#146;s employment agreement and the EBPP&nbsp;3A, as applicable, we have agreed to pay severance benefits of two times base salary in a lump sum if we terminate the executive
officer&#146;s active employment without Cause as it is defined in the applicable document (one and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">one-half</FONT> times base salary if the executive became a participant in EBPP&nbsp;3A after
February&nbsp;22,&nbsp;2011). We have agreed to provide to Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey as additional severance payments an amount equal to two times his target award under the OHIP, and to other named executive officers, additional severance payments in the
amount that the executive officer would have been eligible to receive under the OHIP for a period of two years (18 months for participants first covered by EBPP&nbsp;3A after February&nbsp;22,&nbsp;2011) following termination. Under
Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey&#146;s employment agreement and EBPP&nbsp;3A, the executive would be entitled to receive a pro rata payment of the OHIP award, if any, earned for the year in which termination occurs. These benefits also are payable if the executive
officer resigns from active employment for Good Reason as it is defined in the applicable document. Good Reason will arise under Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey&#146;s employment agreement in the event of a diminution of his title, duties, responsibilities, a
material breach of the employment agreement by the Company, any adverse amendment to the DB&nbsp;SERP or EBPP&nbsp;3A affecting Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey or his removal or failure to be reelected to the Board. Good Reason arises under the EBPP&nbsp;3A if we
appoint a new Chief Executive Officer, and during the first two years of his or her tenure, the executive officer&#146;s position, authority, duties or responsibilities are materially diminished or base salary is materially reduced. If
Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey&#146;s or an executive officer&#146;s employment is terminated for reasons other than for Cause, or if the executive officer terminates for Good Reason, the Company will continue the executive&#146;s
</FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">82 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">
welfare benefits for a period of two years. For executives first covered by EBPP&nbsp;3A after February&nbsp;22,&nbsp;2011, welfare benefit coverage will continue for 18 months. Ms.&nbsp;Turner
is the only named executive officer first covered by EBPP&nbsp;3A after February&nbsp;22,&nbsp;2011. Coverage for disability and participation in all <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">tax-qualified</FONT> retirement plans will not be continued.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">If an executive officer is under age 55 and his or her employment is terminated for reasons other than for Cause, or if the executive officer
terminates for Good Reason, the executive will be eligible to exercise all vested stock options and a prorated portion of his or her unvested stock options held on the date of separation from service for a period of 120 days following separation. If
the executive officer is age 55 or older (with five or more years of continuous service with respect to stock options granted on or after April&nbsp;28,&nbsp;2011) and his or her employment is terminated for reasons other than for Cause, or if the
executive terminates for Good Reason, the executive will be entitled to exercise (provided any vesting requirement has been satisfied as of the date of exercise) any outstanding stock options until the earlier of three or five years (based on the
provisions of the individual grant) from the date of termination or the expiration of the options. In addition, if an executive officer&#146;s employment is terminated for reasons other than for Cause, or if the executive officer terminates for Good
Reason, the executive will receive payment for a prorated portion of any unvested RSUs held on the date of separation from service. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The
following table summarizes the incremental amounts that would have been payable to the named executive officer had his or her employment terminated on December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2013, under circumstances entitling the officer to severance benefits as
described above. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Special provisions apply if a Change in Control occurs. In general, a Change in Control will occur if the Milton Hershey School Trust no longer owns voting control of the Company and another person or
group acquires 30% or more of the combined voting power of our voting stock; there is an unwelcome change in a majority of the members of our Board, or, if after consummation of a merger or similar business transaction or a sale of substantially all
of our assets, the Milton Hershey School Trust does not own voting control of the merged or acquiring company. </FONT></P>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Executives who participate in the Hershey Retirement Plan will receive a lump sum equal to their Basic Pay Credit percentage under that plan times the
sum of their base salary and annual incentive earnings times the number of years in their Severance Period (two, or, if less, the number of full and fractional years from the date of termination to the executive&#146;s 65</FONT><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1"><SUP STYLE="vertical-align:baseline; position:relative; bottom:.8ex">th</SUP></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"> birthday, but not less than one). Executives who do not participate
in the Hershey Retirement Plan will receive a lump sum calculated with the same formula but replacing the Basic Pay Credit percentage with the Core Retirement Plan contribution rate. IRS limitations imposed on the Hershey Retirement Plan and 401(k)
Plan will not apply for this purpose; </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:2px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Outplacement services up to $35,000 and reimbursement for financial counseling and tax preparation services for two years;
</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:2px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">For participants in the DB&nbsp;SERP an enhanced benefit reflecting an additional two years of credit; and </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:2px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">For participants in the DC&nbsp;SERP an enhanced benefit reflecting a cash payment equal to the applicable percentage rate multiplied by his or her
annual base salary and last annual incentive pay calculated as if such amounts were paid during the years in the executive&#146;s severance period. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In February&nbsp;2011, we amended the EBPP&nbsp;3A to eliminate the excise tax gross-up for all participants. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Our Incentive Plan provides for full vesting of all unvested replacement awards relating to outstanding stock options and RSUs (including accrued cash credits equivalent to dividends that would have been
earned had the executive held Common Stock instead of RSUs) granted on or after April&nbsp;28,&nbsp;2011, for a termination after a Change in Control. The table below summarizes the severance payments and all other amounts that would have vested and
become payable if a Change in Control occurred and the executive officer&#146;s employment terminated on December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2013. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">87 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc634600_23"></A>PROPOSAL NO. 3 &#150; NON-BINDING ADVISORY VOTE TO APPROVE THE
COMPENSATION OF OUR NAMED EXECUTIVE OFFICERS </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>What am I voting on? </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">You are being asked to vote on a proposal commonly known as a &#147;say-on-pay&#148; proposal, which gives you the opportunity to approve or not approve, on a non-binding advisory basis, our executive
officer compensation program, policies and practices through the following resolution: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#147;RESOLVED, that the stockholders
of The Hershey Company approve, on an advisory basis, the compensation of the Company&#146;s named executive officers, as described in the Compensation Discussion and Analysis, the compensation tables and the accompanying narrative disclosure set
forth, pursuant to Item&nbsp;402 of Regulation S-K, in the Company&#146;s proxy statement for the 2014 annual meeting of stockholders.&#148; </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>What factors should I consider in voting on this proposal? </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">We urge you to consider the various factors regarding our executive compensation program, policies and practices as detailed in the Compensation Discussion and Analysis, beginning on
page&nbsp;<B></B>44<B></B>. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">As discussed at length in the Compensation Discussion and Analysis, we believe that our executive compensation
program is competitive and governed by pay-for-performance principles. We emphasize compensation opportunities that reward results. Our stock ownership requirements and use of stock-based incentives reinforce the alignment of the interests of our
executives with those of our long-term stockholders. In doing so, our executive compensation program supports our strategic objectives and mission. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Why is this proposal being submitted to the stockholders? </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">This &#147;say-on-pay&#148;
proposal is being submitted to you to obtain the advisory vote of the stockholders in accordance with the Dodd-Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act, or Dodd-Frank Act, section 14A of the Securities Exchange Act of 1934, as amended,
and the SEC&#146;s rules. The Dodd-Frank&nbsp;Act requires that public companies give their stockholders the opportunity to cast advisory votes relating to executive compensation at the first annual meeting of stockholders held after
January&nbsp;21,&nbsp;2011, and no less frequently than once every three years thereafter. At the 2011 annual meeting, the Board of Directors recommended, and our stockholders approved, holding a &#147;say-on-pay&#148; vote every year. Accordingly,
we will hold a &#147;say-on-pay&#148; vote annually until the 2017 annual meeting, when stockholders will be asked to vote again on how frequently we should hold the &#147;say-on-pay&#148; vote. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Is this vote binding on the Board of Directors? </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Because your vote is advisory, it will not be binding upon the Board of Directors. However, as noted in the Compensation Discussion and Analysis, our Board of Directors (including our Compensation and
Executive Organization Committee) will take into account the outcome of the vote when considering future decisions affecting executive compensation as it deems appropriate. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>How many votes will be required for approval of Proposal No.&nbsp;3? </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Approval of Proposal
No.&nbsp;3, the advisory, non-binding &#147;say-on-pay&#148; proposal, requires that a majority of the votes of the shares of Common Stock and Class B Common Stock present and entitled to vote on the proposal are cast in favor of the proposal.
</FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">88 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>How does the Board of Directors recommend that I vote? </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P><div style="width:100%;margin-left:0%; margin-right:0%;border:solid 1pt;padding-top:2px;padding-bottom:3px">
<P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px;padding-top:12px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Board of Directors unanimously recommends that stockholders </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">vote <B>FOR</B> Proposal No. 3, the advisory resolution approving the </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">compensation of the Company&#146;s named executive officers as </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px;padding-bottom:12px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">described in this proxy&nbsp;statement. </FONT></P></div> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc634600_25"></A>SECTION 16(a) BENEFICIAL OWNERSHIP REPORTING COMPLIANCE </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>What is section 16(a) of the Securities Exchange Act of 1934? </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Section&nbsp;16(a) of the Securities Exchange Act of 1934, as amended, requires our directors and executive officers and any person who is the beneficial owner of more than 10% of our outstanding Common
Stock to file reports with the SEC showing their ownership and changes in ownership of Hershey securities. Based solely on our examination of these reports and on written representations provided to us, it is our opinion that all reports for 2013
were timely filed. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc634600_26"></A>CERTAIN TRANSACTIONS AND RELATIONSHIPS </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>What is being disclosed in this section? </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">SEC regulations require that we disclose any transaction, or series of similar transactions, since the beginning of 2013, or any currently proposed
transactions, in which the Company was or is to be a participant, in which the amount involved exceeds $120,000 and in which any of the following persons had or will have a direct or indirect material interest: </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Our directors or nominees for director; </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:2px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Our executive officers; </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:2px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Persons owning more than 5% of any class of our outstanding voting securities; or </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:2px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The immediate family members of any of the persons identified in the preceding three bullets. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The SEC refers to these types of transactions as <I>related person transactions</I> and to the persons listed in the bullets as <I>related persons</I>.
The SEC is concerned about related person transactions because such transactions, if not properly monitored, may present risks of conflicts of interest or the appearance of conflicts of interest. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Does the Company have a policy to review, approve or ratify related person transactions? </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Our Board has adopted a Related Person Transaction Policy that governs the review, approval or ratification of related person transactions. The Related Person Transaction Policy may be viewed on the
Company&#146;s website, <I>www.thehersheycompany.com</I>, in the Investors section. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Under our policy, each related person transaction, and
any significant amendment or modification to a related person transaction, must be reviewed and approved or ratified by a committee of our Board composed solely of independent directors who have no interest in the transaction. We refer
</FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">89 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">
to each such committee as a Reviewing Committee. The policy also permits the disinterested members of the full Board to act as a Reviewing Committee. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Board has designated the Governance Committee as the Reviewing Committee primarily responsible for the administration of the Related Person
Transaction Policy. In addition, the Board has designated special Reviewing Committees to oversee certain transactions involving the Company and Hershey Trust Company, the Milton Hershey School Trust and companies owned by the Milton Hershey School
Trust, which we describe in further detail in the answer to the fourth question in this section below. Finally, the policy provides that the Compensation and Executive Organization Committee will review and approve, or review and recommend to the
Board for approval, any employment relationship or transaction involving an executive officer of the Company and any related compensation. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">When reviewing, approving or ratifying a related person transaction, the Reviewing Committee will examine several things, including the approximate
dollar value of the transaction and all material facts about the related person&#146;s interest in, or relationship to, the transaction. If the related person transaction involves an outside director or nominee for director, the Reviewing Committee
also may consider whether the transaction would compromise the director&#146;s status as an &#147;independent director,&#148; &#147;outside director&#148; or &#147;non-employee director&#148; under our Corporate Governance Guidelines and rules and
regulations of the New York Stock Exchange, the Internal Revenue Code or the Securities Exchange Act of 1934, as amended. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Was the Company
a participant in any related person transactions in 2013, or does the Company currently contemplate being a participant in any related person transactions in 2014, involving its directors, executive officers or their immediate family members?
</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">We were not a participant in any related person transactions in 2013, and we do not currently contemplate being a participant in any
related person transactions in 2014, involving our directors, executive officers or their immediate family members. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Was the Company a
participant in any related person transactions in 2013, or does the Company currently contemplate being a participant in any related person transactions in 2014, involving a stockholder owning more than 5% of any class of the Company&#146;s voting
securities? </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">We engage in certain transactions with Milton Hershey School, the Milton Hershey School Trust and companies owned by the
Milton Hershey School Trust. As discussed in the next question, many of these transactions are immaterial, <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">ordinary-course</FONT> transactions and are not considered related person transactions. However, from time to
time we may engage in certain related person transactions with the Milton Hershey School Trust and its affiliates. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Our Board has directed
that a special Reviewing Committee composed of the directors elected by the holders of the Common Stock voting separately as a class review and make recommendations to the Board regarding these transactions. However, the Board also has directed
that, if there are no directors on the Board who were elected by the holders of our Common Stock voting separately, such transactions will be reviewed by the independent members of the Executive Committee who have no affiliation with the Milton
Hershey School Trust or its affiliates. In addition to the process outlined above, the Board has authorized the independent directors having no affiliation with the Milton Hershey School Trust or its affiliates to designate another special Reviewing
Committee to review these transactions. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">90 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">We were not a participant in any related person transactions in 2013, and do not currently contemplate being
a participant in any related person transactions in 2014, involving the Milton Hershey School Trust, its affiliates or any other stockholder owning more than 5% of any class of the Company&#146;s voting securities. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Did the Company engage in other transactions with the Milton Hershey School Trust or its affiliates during 2013? </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">During 2013, we engaged in transactions in the ordinary course of our business with Milton Hershey School, the Milton Hershey School Trust, and companies
owned by the Milton Hershey School Trust. These transactions involved the sale and purchase of goods and services as well as the leasing of real estate at market rates. The transactions were primarily with Hershey Entertainment&nbsp;&amp; Resorts
Company, a company that is wholly owned by the Milton Hershey School Trust. All sales and purchases were made on terms and at prices we believe were generally available in the marketplace and were in amounts that were not material to us or to the
Milton Hershey School Trust. Therefore, they are not related person transactions and did not have to be approved under our Related Person Transaction Policy. However, because of our relationship with the Milton Hershey School Trust, we have elected
to disclose the aggregate amounts of our purchase and sale transactions for your information. In this regard: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Our total sales to these entities in 2013 were approximately $1.8 million; and </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:2px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Our total purchases from these entities in 2013 were approximately $3.2 million. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">We do not expect that the types of transactions or the amount of payments will change materially in 2014. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In prior years we made monetary contributions to the M.&nbsp;S. Hershey Foundation to support the capital campaign for The Hershey Story, The Museum on
Chocolate Avenue, a facility constructed by the Foundation in Hershey, Pennsylvania, to honor the life and legacy of our founder, Milton S. Hershey. We have contributed $1.0 million to the Foundation to support The Hershey Story&#146;s capital
campaign; however, no monetary contributions were made in 2013. The Foundation was established by Mr.&nbsp;Hershey in 1935 to provide educational and cultural benefits for the residents of Derry Township, Pennsylvania, where the community of Hershey
is located. The Foundation is separate from the Milton Hershey School Trust; however, it is governed by a board of managers appointed by Hershey Trust Company, as trustee for the trust established by Mr.&nbsp;Hershey to benefit the Foundation, from
the membership of the board of directors of Hershey Trust Company. James&nbsp;M. Mead, an independent member of our Board of Directors and an independent member of the board of directors of Hershey Trust Company and the board of managers of Milton
Hershey School, also is a member of the board of managers of the Foundation. Mr.&nbsp;Mead received no compensation for his service on the board of managers of the Foundation. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Company leases to Hershey Entertainment&nbsp;&amp;&nbsp;Resorts Company a portion of a building owned and occupied by the Company in Hershey, Pennsylvania. The leased area consists of approximately
22,500 square feet of storage space in the building that is not being utilized currently by the Company. The lease was first entered into on January&nbsp;1, 2011, and had a term of one year. The lease permits Hershey
Entertainment&nbsp;&amp;&nbsp;Resorts Company to renew the lease for subsequent one-year terms and, if space is available, to request an increase in the area occupied. Hershey&nbsp;Entertainment&nbsp;&amp;&nbsp;Resorts Company renewed the lease for
additional one-year terms beginning January&nbsp;1 of 2013 and 2014, and in 2013 elected to increase its total occupied area. The lease is on terms we believe are generally available in the marketplace and is not material to us or
Hershey&nbsp;Entertainment&nbsp;&amp; Resorts Company. Rent during 2013 was $180,000 and for 2014 is expected be $270,000, which amounts include a pro rata allocation of utilities, insurance, maintenance and other operating costs. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">91 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc634600_27"></A>INFORMATION ABOUT THE 2015 ANNUAL MEETING </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>When is the 2015 annual meeting of stockholders? </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Our 2015 annual meeting of stockholders will be held on April&nbsp;28,&nbsp;2015. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>What is the
deadline to submit a proposal for inclusion in the proxy materials for the 2015 annual meeting? </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">To be eligible for inclusion in the proxy
materials for the 2015 annual meeting, a stockholder proposal must be received by our Corporate Secretary by the close of business on November&nbsp;18, 2014, and comply in all respects with applicable rules of the SEC. Stockholder proposals should
be addressed to The Hershey Company, Attn: Corporate Secretary, 100 Crystal A Drive, Hershey, Pennsylvania 17033-0810. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>What procedure
should I follow if I intend to present a proposal or nominate a director from the floor at the 2015 annual meeting? </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">A stockholder may
present a proposal not included in our 2015 proxy materials from the floor of the 2015 annual meeting only if our Corporate Secretary receives notice of the proposal, along with additional information required by our by-laws, during the time period
beginning at the close of business on December&nbsp;30, 2014, and ending at the close of business on January&nbsp;29, 2015. Notice should be addressed to The Hershey Company, Attn:&nbsp;Corporate Secretary, 100 Crystal A Drive, Hershey, Pennsylvania
17033-0810. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The notice must contain the following additional information: </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

Company (&#147;Vanguard&#148;),* as trustee of the 401(k) Plan or as custodian appointed by Banco Popular de Puerto Rico, trustee of the PR 401(k) Plan, as applicable. <I>If you are a participant in either plan, this paragraph (and not the paragraph

the shares of Common Stock allocated to the accounts of other participants in that plan who have not submitted voting instructions by the voting deadline. If Vanguard receives your properly marked and executed card on or before April&nbsp;24, 2014,
Vanguard will vote these shares in the manner directed by you. <I>If direction is not given or is received after April&nbsp;24, 2014, </I>Vanguard will vote these shares in the 401(k) Plan or PR 401(k) Plan, as applicable, in the same proportion,
